 More specifically, instead of assuming that much of status consumption
 occurs through visible commodities (clothing, shoes, jewelry etc.) we use
 a framework of demand under risk to evaluate consumer choice under the
 uncertainty with promotion or security of one's social rank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective of the proposed model is to seek minimum conditions in an
 environment of uncertainty where status consumption could develop.
 In the stochastic setting where we define a competition for future wealth,
 non-durable consumption is viewed both as an expense and a potential risky
 position for a future jump in social ranking.
 For example, education is viewed as an expense that both increases the
 value of the consumer in an employment market immediately and rises her
 expectations for a future that may create more opportunities (forgoing
 education would similarly both lower her immediate value and shut down
 future opportunities).
 The utility from education to the consumer therefore comprises both of
 its value in the market and the probability of achieving success.
 Viewing consumption choices as a lottery scheme where status consumption
 may be riskier than education - we explore how varied risk-attitudes could
 result in long-term differences under rising and declining phases of economic
 growth.
 The effect of taxation and social differences on status consumption are
 discussed as well.
\end_layout

