\begin_layout Standard
To pin down a particular notion of status we rely on a social-deference
 view of status provided by Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We find that the snob-bandwagon view of consumption provides more tractability
 and descriptive significance than the mutually opposing mechanisms - pecuniary
 emulation and invidious comparison - that were identified by Veblen.
 This is because the extreme wealth differences in an economy would typically
 segregate the status consumption across social groups - thereby limiting
 the extent to which the not-so rich may emulate the rich (pecuniary emulation)
 or care much about the lifestyles of the ultra-rich (invidious comparison).
\end_layout

\end_inset

- who motivate a case for a ranking order of status so that a consumer always
 attempts to move herself up in the order.
 Incorporating utility under risk, we attach probabilities to the consumer's
 future (relative) wealth positions that motivate her risk-allocation in
 a stochastic process of wealth.
 The role that durable and non-durable consumption play towards altering
 the existing wealth order are fundamentally different in the model - as
 the former changes consumer's wealth immediately whereas the latter encompasses
 the risky investments in hope for future wealth gains (assuming that needs
 are a deterministic function of one's wealth).
 The consumer's position in the uncertain wealth order is viewed as a long-term
 security of the consumer from extreme fluctuations in her (higher) wealth.
 This is also the sense in which status - despite the different measurements
 varying by respective social contexts - is interpreted in the sociological
 sciences where it is tracked as a vector of income, education and occupation
 (see Michelson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Psake et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PsakiSeidman2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a few examples).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But viewing status as a mere demographic vector ignores its dynamic nature
 and undermines the demand for status goods which influence a consumer's
 perception of status - thus ruling out the presence of status consumption.
 Not only can status be changed with consumption but as a social psychological
 concern of a particular social unit it is also subject to localised concerns
 in ways the long-term characteristics are not.
 Thus while a researcher could view a high-status individual as someone
 who has either or both of high income and a high (inter-generational) probabili
ty to move towards the high income group (stability), the consumer at local
 levels may be motivated by the particular short-term concerns within her
 social unit that are not observable at the researcher's level of observation.
 To separate these concerns we term the former uncertainty as the 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 uncertainty in future wealth so that a low-status individual is someone
 who has either or both of low net worth and a low probability of transition
 to high net worth (and vice versa).
 The latter uncertainty - which a consumer attaches to her future wealth
 subject to the social unit - is referred to as the 
\shape italic
subjective
\shape default
 uncertainty.
 The demarcation of two uncertainties in this manner might seem unnecessary
 but the goal is only to highlight the role of perception of risk in wealth
 subject to varied risk-aversion levels.
 They are in fact merely an implication of the notion of subjective probability
 and the association of demand with reference levels
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The arguments for subjective probability have been around at least since
 Keynes.
 A more formal treatment of subjective probability is offered by de Finetti
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vonPlato2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Savage
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Savage1972"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 .
 The term personal probability (instead of perceived probability) is used
 by Savage to imply a probability associated with a consequence.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The collective subjective uncertainties are reconciled in the model at the
 higher level of observation with a common wealth process.
 This is necessary because i) the subjective perceptions of all consumers
 are constrained by the long-term resources in the economy and ii) consumer's
 private view of future wealth is revealed to the external world (i.e.
 other participants) through consumption.
 In other words, what matters in the long-run is whether the risky investments
 (consumption) have resulted in a higher state of wealth (and thus status)
 or not.
 Also, regardless of what a consumer may believe, the wealth process changes
 only in response to actions taken on those beliefs rather than the beliefs
 themselves.
 The utility in the consumer's subjective plane of choice is a combination
 of current wealth value and the perceived uncertainty associated with the
 future level of wealth and considers both the uncertainties.
 The consumer decisions - which correspond to various options with different
 probabilities of wealth gain - are made by adjusting the observed uncertainty
 with the weights corresponding to one's risk-aversion level.
 We represent these weights with a specific probability weighting function
 - so that a higher probability for the wealth gain (e.g.
 prospects after gaining entry to a club or education) perceived by a risk-seeki
ng consumer corresponds to a higher (subjective) weight for the same 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 probability and a higher probability of loss of one's wealth or status
 (e.g.
 that of the threat of immigration or a market downturn) perceived by a
 risk-averse consumer would correspond to a lower (
\shape italic
subjective
\shape default
) weight for the 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate this mechanism with an example, consider three consumers with
 different occupations in a small economy that consists of an academic,
 a sportsperson and an investor - who are all of the same age, have the
 same starting wealth and share the same reference point for future wealth.
 Solely due to the nature of payoffs in their respective occupations, each
 of them may have different views on the likelihood of doubling their wealth
 in their lifetimes 
