 Here the choices for investments to future wealth are formulated as a lottery
 scheme enumerating the options with varying levels of risk.
 Explaining how status consumption fits into this framework, we proceed
 to discuss the normative concern of a fair value of status consumption
 for a given process of wealth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At a more fundamental level, the underlying issue - which the two uncertainties
 attempt to model - is the delay or barrier to the flow of risk-related
 information in the consumer markets.
 The subjective and observed uncertainties dissociate only because information
 is consumed differently at the levels of societal organisation - thus making
 the perceived uncertainties at different levels relevant.
 There is little doubt that the differences in purchasing power between
 sections of a society and a resulting desire for mobility drives consumption
 and economy (see Smith 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SmithMoralSentiments"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) but the consumers not having uniform perceptions about their future may
 also result in a market of goods that provide a perceived security (see
 commentaries from Hirsch
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Galbraith 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GalbraithEssential,GalbraithAffluent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ).
 Here, a probabilistic view of utility could help explain the demand for
