\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the risk of belaboring this point, let us contrast the above stochastic
 approach with the model implied by the permanent income hypothesis (PIH)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FriedmanConsumption1957"
literal "false"

\end_inset

- which views the observed income of a consumer as the sum of transitory
 and permanent components.
 It also assumes that consumption is proportional to the permanent component
 since the transient components cancel out in the long-term.
 There are two ways in which a stochastic approach is fundamentally different
 from PIH.
 First, the strong condition of an independence (zero-correlation) between
 the transitory component and the permanent components in the PIH is much
 stronger than what is needed for the stochastic wealth process.
 Second, PIH cannot handle anomalies such as a consumer purchasing insurance
 and participating in a lottery at the same time.
 Under PIH, it follows that a low-income individual with uncertainty in
 her income would always maintain buffer stocks in order to smoothen her
 income - thereby preventing her from engaging in a simultaneous lottery
 and insurance
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This anomaly remains even after incorporating the relative income approach
 (see Duesenberry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duesenberry1949"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 ) within PIH
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FriedmanConsumption1957"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A utility that accounts for loss-aversion with respect to a reference point
 and a non-linear response to the probabilities - on the other hand - can
 handle such anomalies.
 The PIH consumer who always minimises volatility could also be viewed within
 the stochastic framework as a loss-averse individual.
 With a direct utility that depends on both risk and loss-aversion, the
 stochastic framework is better suited to explain the apparent paradox of
 status consumption - where a consumer takes a disproportionate irrational
 risk by either hoping for social-mobility in the long-term (with bandwagon
 items) or being more exclusive than wealth alone may permit (with snob
 items)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Friedman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FriedmanConsumption1957"
literal "false"

\end_inset

