\begin_layout Standard
We had set ourselves to find the minimal conditions under uncertainty that
 justify an expenditure on status goods.
 The proposed model does this by viewing status consumption as a long-term
 security arising due to non-uniform perceptions of uncertainty.
 We believe that to understand the problems of wealth inequality, one should
 aim to understand how social-occupational structures drive risk-aversion
 levels in addition to focusing on the wealth-differences among the participants
 in an economy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There may be a need to review the notions of status consumption â€“ which
 is often seen as wasteful â€“ in light of the perceived security they may
 provide.
 To provide a normative view of status consumption, we have attempted to
 address three key issues relating to status consumption.
 First is the issue of a fair value of status consumption.
 We contend that viewing status consumption as a result of asymmetries in
 future hopes for riches could be more appropriate than its view as a mere
 social waste.
 This more generic framework for the fair value of status consumption could
 be more useful in a comparison of status consumption across disparate economies
 (such as those in the developing and the developed world).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second issue is the effect of social privileges on status consumption
 - privileges being merely a power to exercise pure subjective influence
 on the consumers.
 As the roots of uncertainty lie in exchangeability
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RichardSubjectiveProbRealThing2004,deFinettiLaPrevision1937"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the very presence of social hierarchy is interpreted as individuals associatin
g a higher subjective probability to the individuals carrying a certain
 characteristics (by considering the individuals with the same characteristics
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

exchangeable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in a private sense).
 The subjective interpretation differs slightly with the deterministic view
 as it allows us to view social differences and occupations as not merely
 an order of wealth - but of future perceptions with respect to a social
 reference group as well (see Karelis
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KarelisPoverty2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a discussion on the role of poverty in consumption and of reference
 levels).
 The stability and security provided by social hierarchies and identities
 can be understood as factors directly influencing the risk-aversion of
 the consumer - factors that also influence the demand for status goods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The opposing choices of security in the short-term vs long-term at the microecon
omic level could correspond to the balance of cooperation and competition
 in societies.
 This relates to the third issue - a measurable effect of taxation on status
 consumption.
 The model provides a quantitative understanding of the sustainability of
 extreme wealth differences which taxation aims to address.
 By relating taxation to the certainty of future wealth i.e.
 by considering taxation as more certain income than expenditure, we incorporate
 the insights from utility under risk to understand how status consumption
 may be transformed with taxation.
 This understanding of the status needs of the consumer would thus be of
 value in the debate on a Pigouvian tax for status goods as well.
\end_layout

